## UK Electricity Rates in 2026 — What You're Actually Paying

From 1 April 2026, Ofgem's energy price cap sets the standard variable electricity rate at **24.67p per kWh**, with a daily standing charge of **54.75p**. This is a 6.7% fall from the previous quarter, bringing the typical household annual bill to around **£1,641**.

But the price cap is just the starting point. If you're charging an EV at home and you're still on a standard variable tariff, you're paying far more than you need to.

**EV-specific tariffs** offer off-peak rates as low as **7.9–9.5p per kWh** — that's 60–70% cheaper than the standard rate. We'll get into the specifics shortly, but the point is simple: your electricity rate is the single biggest factor in your charging costs, and it's the one thing you can control.

